<dl id="n25180c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25180c">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25180c"> 180(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Pantokreator <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n25180c"><li>FW 411.15 </li><li><a href="../../flex/pA/lexpA.htm#n25180c">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/pA/l39pA.htm#n25180c">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n25180c">MS VI.F.5-4</ms> </li><li>JJA not reproduced <a name="pAd8" href="../../ff/fdra/pda.htm#pAd8">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/pA/pAd8.htm#n25180c">Draft: III&sect;1A.8</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">When from the superstitions of the past the Assyrians and the Persians attained to the conception of a supreme god ruling all the others, they still drew him as a human being with the wings and tail of an eagle&mdash;as we see him represented, not only at Nineveh, but on the tomb of Darius, where this form represents Ahura-mazda the Creator. So too, when the Byzantines broke away from the earlier law of the Church, they pictured the <mark>Pantokrator</mark> (or &ldquo;ruler of all&rdquo;) as an aged king on his throne. <small> Claude R. Conder, <a name="CRRM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#CRRM"><cite title="source">The Rise of Man</cite></a> (1908) 161</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Pantocrator: a Greek word meaning &lsquo;ruler of all.&rsquo; </mm> </dd></dl>
